# Getting Started Guides — Authoring Rule

Apply this rule whenever you are asked to create or edit a Getting Started guide in this repository.

## Where guides live

All Getting Started guides belong in:
```
docusaurus/docs/getting-started/getting-started-guides/
```

---

## File naming

Use lowercase kebab-case, always prefixed with `getting-started-with-`:
```
getting-started-with-[topic].mdx
```

Examples:
- `getting-started-with-your-team.mdx`
- `getting-started-with-accounts-and-product-activation.mdx`

---

## Frontmatter

Every guide must include the following frontmatter fields:

```mdx
---
title: "Getting Started: [Topic Name]"
sidebar_label: [Short Label]
description: "[One sentence describing what the guide helps the reader accomplish.]"
sidebar_position: [number]
tags: [getting-started, relevant-tag, another-tag]
keywords: [keyword one, keyword two, keyword three]
---
```

- `title` always follows the pattern `"Getting Started: [Topic]"`
- `sidebar_label` is a short version of the topic (2-4 words max)
- `description` must not contain em dashes
- `sidebar_position` should follow the order in the planned guide series (1 = first guide)

---

## Document structure

Every guide must follow this structure in order:

### 1. H1 title
Matches the frontmatter `title`.

### 2. Intro paragraph
1-3 sentences. Explain what the topic is, why it matters to a beginner, and what the guide covers. Write for someone brand new to the platform.

### 3. Plan restriction note (if applicable)
If any feature in the guide requires a paid or higher-tier plan, add a `:::note` immediately after the intro:

```mdx
:::note
Some features covered in this guide are only available on certain plans. [View plan details](https://www.yoursite.com/pricing)
:::
```

**Never name specific plan tiers.** Always use generic language like "certain plans", "select plans", or "paid plans" and link to the pricing page.

### 4. Getting Started Checklist
A numbered list linking to each major step in the guide. Use colons, not em dashes, to separate the step name from its description:

```mdx
## Getting Started Checklist

1. [Step one title](#step-1-step-one-title): brief description of what this step covers
2. [Step two title](#step-2-step-two-title): brief description
3. [Step three title](#step-3-step-three-title): brief description
```

### 5. Steps (H2 sections)
Each step is a `##` section. Open with 1-2 sentences of context, then a navigation path if relevant, then H3 sub-sections for each sub-task.

Navigation paths use this format:
```
Navigate to **[Product]** > **Section** > **Page**.
```

End every step section with:
```mdx
[Back to checklist](#getting-started-checklist)

---
```

### 6. What's next
Close every guide with a `## What's next` section. Link only to pages that actually exist in the repo. Do not link to guides that have not been created yet.

```mdx
## What's next

Brief sentence about what the reader is ready to do now.

- **[Page Title](/path/to/existing/doc/)**: One-line description
- **[Page Title](/path/to/existing/doc/)**: One-line description
```

---

## Writing style rules

### Em dashes: never use them
Em dashes (`—`) are not allowed anywhere in the document, including the frontmatter description. Replace them with:
- A colon (`:`) when introducing a list or expansion
- A comma (`,`) when used as a parenthetical
- A period (`.`) to start a new sentence
- Parentheses `( )` for asides

**Wrong:** `This is a white-label platform — meaning you can brand it as your own.`
**Right:** `This is a white-label platform, meaning you can brand it as your own.`

**Wrong:** `— your company name, logo, and colors`
**Right:** `: your company name, logo, and colors`

### Plan tier names: never use specific names
Never reference specific plan names (e.g. Growth, Scale, Starter, Pro). Instead use:
- "certain plans"
- "select plans"
- "paid plans"
- "some subscription tiers"

Always follow with a link to your pricing page.

### Heading casing
Use sentence case for all headings. Only capitalize the first word and any proper nouns or product names. Do not title-case every word.

**Wrong:** `### Add Your Company Name And Logo`
**Right:** `### Add your company name and logo`

Product names and proper nouns should always be capitalized as they are officially written (e.g. Partner Center, Business App, Stripe, Google).

### Tone
- Write for a **beginner** who is brand new to the platform
- Use "you" and "your clients" (not "the user" or "the partner")
- Be direct and instructional
- Use numbered lists for sequential steps, bullet lists for non-sequential info

### Step instructions
Each individual action in a step should be a numbered list item. Bold all UI element names (buttons, field labels, menu items, tab names):

```mdx
1. Go to **[Product]** > **Administration** > **My Team**.
2. Click **Invite team member**.
3. Enter a name and email address.
4. Click **Send**.
```

---

## Admonitions

Use admonitions to call out important information. Choose the right type:

| Type | Use for |
|---|---|
| `:::note` | Plan restrictions, behavior caveats, things that may vary |
| `:::tip` | Best practices, recommendations, time-saving advice |
| `:::warning` | File format requirements, things that will cause errors if wrong |
| `:::info` | Prerequisites, related settings the reader should know about |

---

## Links

### Internal links
- Always verify a link resolves to a real page before including it
- Use root-relative paths starting with `/`
- To link to a specific section, append the anchor (e.g., `/page/#section-heading`)
- Never link to a Getting Started guide that does not yet exist — use plain text instead

### External links
- Use full URLs
- Always open in the same tab

---

## Tables

Use tables for comparison or decision-making content. Avoid em dashes in table cells — use "N/A" or rephrase instead.

```mdx
| Column A | Column B | Column C |
|---|---|---|
| **Item** | When to use | When not to use |
```

---

## Before creating a guide: research checklist

Before writing a new guide, always:

1. **Read the existing source docs** for the topic in the repo.
2. **Verify all links** resolve to real pages before including them.
3. **Do not duplicate** content that already exists — summarize it and link to the full reference instead.
4. **Target audience**: guides are for beginners setting up the platform for the first time.
